---
const sections = [
  {
    n: "01 — Architecture",
    title: "One codebase the team can actually own",
    body: [
      "I built the theme object-oriented from the ground up — namespaced classes with PSR-4 autoloading, each one doing a single job: setup, assets, the block editor, post types, the menu. No 2,000-line functions.php, no spaghetti.",
      "On top of that I built 21 custom Gutenberg blocks for the content the brand actually uses — heroes, product features, FAQ, case-study grids — and committed every field definition to the repo as JSON. That means the build is reproducible and nothing important lives only in a database that can't be version-controlled. The payoff is the part that matters to the brand, not just to me: every page is editable in Gutenberg by a non-technical editor, while the markup never slips out of engineering control.",
    ],
  },
  {
    n: "02 — Front end",
    title: "Rendered on the server, enhanced in the browser",
    body: [
      "I had a rule for the front end: render the structure on the server, then add behaviour with the lightest possible layer on top. No single-page app, no framework weight for what is, mostly, a content site.",
      "The navigation is the clearest example. A custom menu walker generates the markup on the server; a thin Alpine.js layer turns it into two different experiences. On mobile it becomes a sliding menu — a small state machine that tracks which panel you're in and which you came from, so moving between levels feels like a native app rather than a page reload. On desktop it becomes a hover-intent mega menu with a deliberate delay so it never flickers, plus full keyboard and screen-reader support — Escape to close, focus handling, the works.",
      "The same restraint runs through commerce. The product and cart quantity controls are custom-built but speak WooCommerce's own language under the hood, dispatching the exact events WooCommerce expects — and the cart update is debounced, so changing a quantity updates once instead of firing on every tap.",
    ],
  },
  {
    n: "03 — Performance",
    title: "Built to stay fast, and to hold up",
    body: [
      "Speed wasn't an afterthought I bolted on at the end — it's baked into how the site loads. Scripts are deferred and sent to the footer, third-party origins are preconnected before the browser needs them, and assets cache-bust automatically when they change. The result is a site that ships with a cumulative layout shift of zero — nothing jumps, nothing reflows, the experience stays stable as the catalogue grows.",
      "I held the quality the same way I held the speed: with tooling, not willpower. The codebase runs against WordPress coding standards and static analysis, and I codified the project's own rules so the standards are enforced as I write rather than caught later. It's the difference between a site that's fast on launch day and one that's still fast — and still maintainable — a year in.",
    ],
  },
];
---

<section class="container py-[40px] md:py-[64px]">
  <div class="grid gap-y-[24px] md:grid-cols-12 md:gap-x-[40px]">
    <h2
      class="md:col-span-3 font-neue-montreal-mono text-[14px] font-light uppercase triangle-after-right text-[#919191]"
      data-reveal
    >
      Engineering
    </h2>
    <div class="flex flex-col gap-[40px] md:col-span-8 md:col-start-5">
      <p class="font-neue-montreal text-[18px] md:text-[22px] leading-[1.5] text-white/80" data-reveal>
        Most of this site is invisible by design. The part you feel — pages that
        load fast, menus that glide open, a cart that just works — sits on top of
        an architecture I built so a small team can run the whole brand without a
        developer in the room.
      </p>
      {sections.map((s) => (
        <div
          class="flex flex-col gap-[16px] border-t border-white/15 pt-[32px]"
          data-reveal
        >
          <span class="font-neue-montreal-mono text-[14px] uppercase text-[#919191]">
            {s.n}
          </span>
          <h3 class="font-neue-montreal font-medium text-[22px] md:text-[28px] leading-[1.2] text-white">
            {s.title}
          </h3>
          {s.body.map((p) => (
            <p class="font-neue-montreal text-[18px] md:text-[22px] leading-[1.5] text-white/80">
              {p}
            </p>
          ))}
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
